{"id":"5e9c305d9b6559241525db56","artists":["5e9b68c77a1236eccfeb1d73"],"title":"Introducing: Advance Base","content":"<p><a rel=\"attachment wp-att-8453\" href=\"https://admin.</p><p>crackintheroad.com/music/8452-introducing-advance-base/attachment/advancebase\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-8453\" title=\"advancebase\" src=\"https://api.crackintheroad.com/uploads/2011/06/advancebase.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"720\" height=\"427\" srcset=\"https://api.crackintheroad.com/images/2011/06/advancebase.jpg 720w, https://api.crackintheroad.com/images/2011/06/advancebase-260x154.jpg 260w, https://api.crackintheroad.com/images/2011/06/advancebase-640x379.jpg 640w, https://api.crackintheroad.com/images/2011/06/advancebase-165x97.jpg 165w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px\" /></a></p>\n<p>So I was walking to work this morning listening to the Classic that is, <em>Etiquette</em>, by the now not functioning <a href=\"https://www.cftpa.org/\"><strong>Casiotone For The Painfully Alone</strong></a>. That record will probably always make me sad, not least because it’s so fucking heart wrenching, but also because I was under the impression that <strong>Owen Ashworth</strong> would never make music again. Rather wonderfully I came home later that day to find this whimsical, spiritually ecstatic tune in my inbox. It’s short, delicate and tells the story of a childhood pony. A new direction, a beautiful song and a perfect end to the day.</p>\n<p><object classid=\"clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000\" width=\"100%\" height=\"81\" codebase=\"https://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0\"><param name=\"allowscriptaccess\" value=\"always\" /><param name=\"src\" value=\"https://player.soundcloud.com/player.swf?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F16351430&width=398&height=84&show_artwork=false&color=3b5998\" /><embed type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" width=\"100%\" height=\"81\" src=\"https://player.soundcloud.